John Edward: Language Skills Essential for World Citizens
The independent schools in Scotland have an excellent state of academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with a series of excellent exam results, as well as individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other initiatives of the entire community.
With more than 30,000 students in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the best service to their students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen career and their position as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain popular and desirable subjects outstanding within schools.
Nelson Mandela said: ‘If you talk to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, you reach his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and a bond of trust with people from other countries.
From the recent exam results of this year, we can conclude that languages are at the top of the ranking, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a high score.
The data collected from 74 schools affiliated with the SCIS show that 72 percent of the students achieved a high score (‘A’) in Mandarin, while 72 percent of the students received German, 69 percent of the students received French, and 63 percent of the students received Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now valued as a professional choice as STEM subjects (science, technology, technology and mathematics) in independent school programmes and elsewhere.
An investigation by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 revealed that 17% of the obstacles to filling vacancies were attributed to a lack of language skills, according to employers.
Thus, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future career.
Now that more and more job vacancies require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Whatever career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future with such a skill for life.
Direct communication with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person an advantage over competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation. French was the only language that surpassed the 10%, with a total of 15%.
This is why investing in language education is now important to today's children.
Several languages, especially those of emerging economies, will offer children a better chance of finding a meaningful job.
In Scotland, schools themselves choose which languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important for the United Kingdom when they look forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest is, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers specializing in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed regardless of the future.
At the moment, it cannot be denied that languages remain vitally important in a global business environment for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be considered as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
Il fout bien le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
