Harvard students attend a course on the importance of adequate rest
A new course at Harvard University this year ensures that all students get more sleep, in an effort to combat the growing macho culture in which it seems cool to study all night and drink a lot of caffeine.
One professor found that the students of the world's largest university often have no idea of the basic principles of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, Professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School, a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, set up the course. As far as he is aware, this is unique in the U.S.
He got the idea to start the course after giving a talk about the influence of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of my speech, a girl came to me and said, "Why am I only hearing this now, in my last year?"
She said that no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me," he said to The Telegraph.
The course, which will be organised for the first time this year, will explain to the students the basic principles of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance and how they also promote their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to organise the course when it was found that students had a serious sleep shortage during the week.
The course takes one hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of the parts, the students see an image of a dorm, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise equipment and books to learn more about the effects of caffeine and light and the way sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a routine when sleeping.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
With the help of a map of the campus, with interactive icons, participants are encouraged to think about their daily routine.
‘We know that this will not change the behaviour of the students immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know all of this, just as people have the right to know the consequences of the choice for cigarettes on their health, added Czeisler.
The culture of nightlife study still exists, he says, and because of modern technology and the growing pressure on students sleep deprivation is an ever greater problem.
Ensure sufficient sleep, of good quality, the student's 'secret weapon' must be to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes the brain to give them a constant hunger feeling.
