The inventor of the World Wide Web plant a new internet to address Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, starts a startup that wants to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrupt, the latest project of the technology legend, is a company based on the open source platform Solid of Berners-Lee.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and which persons have access to which information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that 'world domination' is the leading idea behind Inrupt.
"We have to do this now," he said about the startup.
"This is a historic moment."
The app uses Solid technology to enable people to make their own 'personal online data storage' or POD.
This allows you to store lists of contacts, activity lists, an agenda, a music library and other personal and professional tools.
It is as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available together via one browser and all at the same time.
What makes POD unique is the fact that it totally depends on the user who has access to which information.
The company calls this "personal empowerment through data".
The idea behind Inrupt is according to CEO John Bruce that the company provides the resources, processes and skills needed to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some developers who have been contracted to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
From this week on, technology developers around the world can make their own decentralised apps using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team are not going to have conversations with "Facebook and Google about introducing or not introducing a complete transformation that puts all their business models on their heads at once."
"We're not asking for their permission."
In a post on Medium published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that "the mission (of Inrupt) is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new web, which is built on Solid".
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on net neutrality.
Even after the start of Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain as founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I am incredibly optimistic about this new era for the web," added Berners-Lee.
