National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
New research carried out on an estate in the Scottish Highlands is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and contribute to future conservation activities.
The study carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland follows the ordinary and the small dwarf bat, the brown large bat and the water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed in key locations around the estate to track the activities of bats throughout the season.
Staff of the NTS and volunteers will also conduct mobile research using hand detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bat's cries and what kind of actions.
Next, a map of the habitat and a report is produced to make a detailed picture of the landscape of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation advisor to the NTS, hopes that the results will show which habitat areas are the most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management, such as making meadows and how we can best maintain the forests for bats and similar species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have decreased significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities affecting sleeping places and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, as can fly catchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials and domestic cat attacks.
Bats are not really blind.
However, their nightly hunting habits make their ears more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use an advanced echo-location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight path.
With the NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares ashore in the country, bats are taken very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts, who conduct regular investigations, sleep site inspections and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even set up the first and only reservation for bats in Scotland at the Threeave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of the ten species of bats in Scotland live.
Landscape manager David Thompson says the estate is the ideal territory for bats.
"Here in Threeave we have a great environment for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But so much about bats is not yet known and therefore the work we do here and in other locations will help us to understand better what they need to thrive."
He stressed the importance of monitoring bats before maintenance activities were carried out, as the possible unconscious destruction of a sleeping area could lead to the death of 400 female bats and their young, potentially eliminating a full local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them or to destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to make a contribution to help.
She said, "We still have to learn a lot about our bats and of many of our species we just don't know how their populations are."
