Syria 'ready' to return refugees, according to Minister of Foreign Affairs
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild the country that has been devastated by a more than seven years of war.
During his speech to the UN General Assembly, Minister for Foreign Affairs, Walid al-Moualem, stated that the situation in his country is improving.
"Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and secure, thanks to the progress made in combating terrorism," he says.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists and to normalise the situation on the ground.
All circumstances are now in place for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they have had to leave because of terrorism and the unilateral economic measures that threatened their daily lives and existence.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled their country since the war began in 2011.
It is estimated that there are about six million people living in the country who need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian regime would welcome help in restoring the devastated land.
However, he stressed that Syria would not accept conditional assistance or assistance from countries that had subsidized the uprising.
