Red glow update: Concentrations decline in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The most recent report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (Florida Commission for the Conservation of Fish and Fauna) shows a general decrease in red glow concentrations in parts of Tampa Bay Area (located on the west coast of Florida in the US).
According to the committee, it is reported that there is a fragmentary increase in the red glow in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which could indicate a decrease in concentrations.
The Red Glow covers an average of 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee County.
There are about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County spots, but in fewer places than last week.
Red glow has also been seen in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations have been reported off the Pinellas County coast over the past week, low to high concentrations off the Hillsborough County coast, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations at or off the Sarasota County coast, background to high concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations at or off Lee County coast, and low concentrations in Collier County.
There are reports of respiratory irritation in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier.
In northwestern Florida, no mention was made of airway irritation in the past week.
